00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.770
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. In today's&nbsp;
video, we want to look at roots of unity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.770 --> 00:00:20.370
which are ostensibly complex numbers that&nbsp;
are equally spaced around the unit circle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.370 --> 00:00:26.490
and obey a seemingly remarkable&nbsp;
algebraic property. These roots&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.490 --> 00:00:32.880
of unity are mainstays in field theory&nbsp;
and are related to cyclotomic fields,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:37.620
which play an important role in abstract&nbsp;
algebra. This topic serves as a good&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:37.620 --> 00:00:43.350
example of a very explicit situation where we&nbsp;
can see that we need to separate two concepts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.350 --> 00:00:47.640
that are currently fused together. We must&nbsp;
approach this in a more organized way.

00:00:48.930 --> 00:00:55.290
The context is the unit circle viewed inside&nbsp;
the complex numbers. Here’s the number 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.290 --> 00:01:03.420
and here is the number i. The unit circle&nbsp;
is given by the equation x² + y² = 1 or,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:03.420 --> 00:01:10.020
in complex analysis terms, the&nbsp;
points z, or complex numbers z,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.020 --> 00:01:18.390
whose quadrance Q(z) = 1. I remind you that the&nbsp;
quadrance of a complex number a + bi is defined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:18.390 --> 00:01:27.240
as a² + b². The absolute value of a complex&nbsp;
number doesn’t really play any role in algebra.

00:01:27.240 --> 00:01:33.990
