00:06:53.870 --> 00:07:00.950
Now, if you’re interested in this, I talked&nbsp;
about it in my algebraic topology series quite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.950 --> 00:07:05.210
some time ago—so I think it’s in Algebraic&nbsp;
Topology, maybe number 3 or something like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.210 --> 00:07:10.370
that. You can have a look. I talked about&nbsp;
how this is a special case of a much more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.370 --> 00:07:16.430
general phenomenon that works for more general&nbsp;
conics. It’s quite interesting. So, this is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.430 --> 00:07:22.040
purely geometrical way, and here’s the algebraic&nbsp;
solution: we know what the parameters for two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:26.690
complex numbers are, and here’s the parameter&nbsp;
for their product. And purely geometrically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:26.690 --> 00:07:31.880
if we know two points on the unit circle, we&nbsp;
can draw the line between them and then draw the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:41.780
line that’s through the point 1, parallel to that&nbsp;
given line, and we get the product. So, two ways&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:48.980
of describing the product of points on the unit&nbsp;
circle in the complex plane—purely algebraically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.980 --> 00:07:57.140
and purely geometrically—and it’s a great exercise&nbsp;
for you to state these precisely and prove them.

00:07:57.140 --> 00:08:05.990
You might be surprised to find out that your&nbsp;
typical undergraduate does not know the contents&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.990 --> 00:08:10.640
of what I just said on that previous slide. That’s&nbsp;
quite surprising to most of them. They think,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:10.640 --> 00:08:16.460
“Wow, why hasn’t somebody told us this before?”&nbsp;
They’ve all been told a different story,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.460 --> 00:08:22.040
and it’s true around the world—doesn’t matter&nbsp;
where you go, they’re all told an alternate story,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:29.150
which is actually much weaker. And at UNSW, we&nbsp;
do this as well, unfortunately. But of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:29.150 --> 00:08:33.920
as the 21st century rolls on, things&nbsp;
are going to be changing. But currently,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.920 --> 00:08:40.430
we do the following old-fashioned thing: we&nbsp;
say that it all has to do with angles. When&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:40.430 --> 00:08:44.870
you’re multiplying complex numbers on the unit&nbsp;
circle, it’s a question about adding angles.

00:08:44.870 --> 00:08:51.290
This is what students actually learn. It’s&nbsp;
very unfortunate. They learn that if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:51.290 --> 00:08:57.950
take the angle formed by the x-axis and z,&nbsp;
and the angle formed by the x-axis and w,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:57.950 --> 00:09:05.360
those are called the argument of z and&nbsp;
the argument of w (those angles). Then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.360 --> 00:09:11.750
the product z * w has an argument or&nbsp;
an angle that is the sum of those two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:11.750 --> 00:09:19.280
angles. So, the argument of z * w equals&nbsp;
the argument of z plus the argument of w.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:28.850
And that’s how you describe the multiplication&nbsp;
of complex numbers geometrically, using angles.

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:38.810
This is applied mathematics, not really pure&nbsp;
mathematics. The reason is that the angles are,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.810 --> 00:09:46.130
in fact, impossible to define properly and to&nbsp;
compute approximately. We can define them and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:46.130 --> 00:09:52.460
deal with them, but defining them precisely and&nbsp;
computing them precisely requires an infinite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:52.460 --> 00:09:59.840
amount of work. So, we cross this border—this&nbsp;
Rubicon—between the world in which we live,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:59.840 --> 00:10:05.000
where you can actually make calculations, and this&nbsp;
imaginary, fictitious world where you’re allowed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:11.390
to do an infinite number of things and obtain&nbsp;
outputs. And it’s this land across this imaginary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:11.390 --> 00:10:16.610
river out there that we’re constantly appealing&nbsp;
to in modern mathematics, but which is actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:16.610 --> 00:10:25.190
illusory—it’s a dream. But that’s ultimately the&nbsp;
dream that’s responsible for this idea of angles.

00:10:26.510 --> 00:10:30.800
Because angles are so difficult&nbsp;
to get your hands on precisely,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.800 --> 00:10:36.680
what happens in undergraduate mathematics&nbsp;
around the world is that we all have this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:36.680 --> 00:10:44.930
tacit agreement that we’re going to stick to two&nbsp;
baby triangles: the 1-1-√2 triangle and the 1-2-√3&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:44.930 --> 00:10:51.500
triangle—the triangle with angles 45 degrees, 45&nbsp;
degrees, and 60 degrees, and 30 degrees. Those are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:57.260
basically the only two triangles that we’re going&nbsp;
to use. So by positioning them in different ways,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.260 --> 00:11:03.110
we can create a bunch of different questions&nbsp;
for undergraduates. And invariably—it’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:03.110 --> 00:11:09.860
remarkable—around the world, whenever students&nbsp;
are asked about specific questions involving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:09.860 --> 00:11:16.070
complex number calculations and involving&nbsp;
angles, invariably 60 degrees, 45 degrees,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:16.070 --> 00:11:22.160
or 30 degrees figure—or some rotation&nbsp;
of them in some of the other quadrants.

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:28.220
It’s actually a very limiting situation. Let’s&nbsp;
look at an example that’s a little bit outside&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:28.220 --> 00:11:34.130
