00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:14.330
Well, that’s a standard computation that most&nbsp;
undergraduates know how to do at some level.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:14.330 --> 00:12:18.650
They know that you have to do a certain number&nbsp;
of things. So, the first thing that probably an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:18.650 --> 00:12:25.760
undergraduate would think is, “Well, we need an&nbsp;
arctan function here.” So, the usual formula is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:25.760 --> 00:12:31.760
that theta equals tan inverse of y/x. So you&nbsp;
take your y-coordinate and your x-coordinate,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:39.860
which in this case are 12/13 and 5/13, and you&nbsp;
take the ratio and you take tan inverse of 12/5.

00:12:39.860 --> 00:12:49.310
But what is tan inverse, or arctan? It’s the same&nbsp;
thing. Well, that’s given by an infinite formula,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:49.310 --> 00:12:53.420
which most undergraduates, after&nbsp;
they’ve done a course in calculus,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:53.420 --> 00:13:04.990
should hopefully know. So, it’s z - z³/3 + z⁵/5&nbsp;
- z⁷/7, and so on. The pattern is pretty clear:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.990 --> 00:13:07.390
there are just odd numbers&nbsp;
in the denominators there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:07.390 --> 00:13:12.550
and the powers in z are going up by&nbsp;
2 through all the odd possibilities.

00:13:12.550 --> 00:13:20.620
Okay, so that’s some kind of infinite expression.&nbsp;
That means that if we want to calculate tan&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:20.620 --> 00:13:29.050
inverse of 12/5, we should just replace z&nbsp;
with 12/5 to get 12/5 - 1/3 of (12/5)³ + 1/5&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:29.050 --> 00:13:37.660
of (12/5)⁵ - 1/7 of (12/5)⁷, and so on. But if&nbsp;
the undergraduate stares at this for a second,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:37.660 --> 00:13:43.900
they will realize, “Wait a minute, something’s&nbsp;
not quite right,” because 12/5 is bigger than 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:53.170
and so these powers—these are powers of 2—they’re&nbsp;
getting big. We are dividing by something that’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:53.170 --> 00:13:59.380
not getting as big as fast, so this thing is going&nbsp;
to blow up. It’s not going to converge and get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.380 --> 00:14:06.790
smaller and smaller as we would like. And&nbsp;
in fact, if the undergraduate thinks back,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:06.790 --> 00:14:12.310
they’ll think, “Okay, actually, this formula&nbsp;
comes with a certain requirement that really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:12.310 --> 00:14:19.030
only works when z has a modulus less than&nbsp;
1, or quadrance less than 1—same thing.”

00:14:19.030 --> 00:14:26.590
So that means that we actually need to try&nbsp;
something else. We need to twist this a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:26.590 --> 00:14:33.040
bit to get at this angle theta. So, how do we&nbsp;
find theta? Well, a clever student might look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:33.040 --> 00:14:37.120
at it this way. They might say, “Okay, this&nbsp;
theta here was a bit problematic because the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:37.120 --> 00:14:44.560
y was bigger than the x, but if we take this&nbsp;
sort of angle here, which is π/2 - theta,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:44.560 --> 00:14:50.290
then that’s a little bit different because&nbsp;
then the x and the y are interchanged.” So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:50.290 --> 00:15:00.010
if we look at π/2 - theta, that’s going to be&nbsp;
tan inverse of now x/y. And the x/y is 5/12.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.010 --> 00:15:07.570
Now we’re in a happier position with respect to&nbsp;
this infinite series defining tan inverse of x/y.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:07.570 --> 00:15:18.620
So we now could take 5/12 - 1/3 of (5/12)³ +&nbsp;
1/5 of (5/12)⁵ - 1/7 of (5/12)⁷, and so on.

00:15:18.620 --> 00:15:27.470
Now, I want you to consider this right here. I&nbsp;
know the average undergraduate learns that you’re&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:27.470 --> 00:15:31.760
not supposed to flinch when you see something&nbsp;
like this, okay? But logically speaking,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:32.840 --> 00:15:37.670
there is something seriously problematic&nbsp;
around here, because we’re being asked to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:37.670 --> 00:15:43.430
do an infinite number of arithmetic operations&nbsp;
here, and this is not even defined. We have not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:43.430 --> 00:15:48.590
defined what we mean by doing an infinite&nbsp;
number of arithmetic operations, okay? So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:48.590 --> 00:15:53.780
it’s not a question of whether the thing exists&nbsp;
or not; it’s just that the actual definition of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:53.780 --> 00:16:01.550
arithmetic that we have always involves adding&nbsp;
a finite number of things. We have not defined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:01.550 --> 00:16:10.280
what it means to add an infinite number of things.&nbsp;
That’s why you have to speak of all the problems:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:16.220
what happens to these numbers actually? What&nbsp;
happens when we get to the z power? Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:16.220 --> 00:16:24.770
we’re taking (5/12)^z. Well, what does that&nbsp;
mean? That’s way beyond the universe in terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.770 --> 00:16:29.660
of writing it down in any reasonable fashion.&nbsp;
And in what sense does it make any sense to add&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:29.660 --> 00:16:35.210
that particular term to what we’ve already&nbsp;
got? It’s clear that this is blowing out on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:35.210 --> 00:16:40.340
us computationally long before we get to&nbsp;
infinity. Long before we get to infinity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:40.340 --> 00:16:47.120
this has just exploded in our faces, and we&nbsp;
just have egg all over us. It’s only because we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.120 --> 00:16:54.500
actually do not make the computations that we’re&nbsp;
allowed to not address the nonsense of it, okay?

00:16:54.500 --> 00:17:01.040
In fact, that’s what happens. Our machines, of&nbsp;
course, know enough not to try to add up all of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:01.040 --> 00:17:05.630
these infinite number of things. The machine knows&nbsp;
that, well, we’re just going to truncate at some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:05.630 --> 00:17:13.730
point and then give the human whatever we have.&nbsp;
So that’s what your machine will do if you ask it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:13.730 --> 00:17:17.960
well, to evaluate tan inverse of 5/12. It will&nbsp;
give you something like this: 0.39479119699976,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:22.970 --> 00:17:30.500
and at that point, it will stop. It will not&nbsp;
actually exhibit three dots, usually. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.500 --> 00:17:37.250
so the undergraduate takes this, which is the&nbsp;
answer to this infinite computation. In fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.250 --> 00:17:42.290
it’s not, okay, but let’s pretend it&nbsp;
is. And then we solve for theta. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:42.290 --> 00:17:45.350
theta is going to be π/2 - tan inverse of 5/12.

00:17:45.350 --> 00:17:54.770
So now we have to procure π/2. Well, π is known&nbsp;
to about five or ten trillion places these days;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:54.770 --> 00:18:01.190
that’s the extent of it. But ostensibly,&nbsp;
we’re taking this π, dividing it by 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:01.190 --> 00:18:09.260
and taking this infinite decimal that we’ve&nbsp;
already computed and taking the difference.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:13.670
So there’s another infinite amount of&nbsp;
work that we’re ostensibly doing. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:13.670 --> 00:18:17.540
you can see this is all just pretending, right?&nbsp;
We’re just pretending here. This is how we do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:17.540 --> 00:18:23.210
modern mathematics when we come to examples.&nbsp;
We are thinking about these infinite things;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:23.210 --> 00:18:26.630
that’s theoretically what we’re doing. But&nbsp;
practically, we’re actually doing something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:26.630 --> 00:18:30.740
quite different. We’re just always working at the&nbsp;
level of floating-point and truncating things and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:30.740 --> 00:18:37.490
pretending that the floating-point truncations are&nbsp;
true reflections of these infinite fantasies that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:37.490 --> 00:18:43.040
we like to dream about. That’s what it is, ladies&nbsp;
and gentlemen—that’s what’s actually happening.

00:18:43.040 --> 00:18:49.160
So the undergraduate comes up with something&nbsp;
like this: so the answer is the angle is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:49.160 --> 00:19:02.840
1.176005207095, and so on. So you can see why&nbsp;
my claim that this is actually the wrong way of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:02.840 --> 00:19:06.680
thinking about things, right? The previous&nbsp;
way of thinking about things, in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:12.890
describing points on the unit circle, involved the&nbsp;
rational parameterization. No infinite processes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:12.890 --> 00:19:22.220
were required, okay? Very concrete. The seeming&nbsp;
advantage of being able to add angles is far&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.940 --> 00:19:28.850
overcompensated by the difficulty in procuring&nbsp;
the angles in the first place. It’s a false&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:28.850 --> 00:19:34.520
economy to think that we’ve saved ourselves&nbsp;
some time or effort because we only need to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:34.520 --> 00:19:39.830
add the angles. In fact, if we actually did&nbsp;
that correctly, there’d be an infinite amount&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:39.830 --> 00:19:45.860
of work. And adding angles is also completely&nbsp;
beyond us, really. So, it’s very important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:45.860 --> 00:19:52.310
to realize that the angle story is an analytic&nbsp;
story, which is just an approximation to things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.310 --> 00:19:58.610
and logically speaking, it’s not in algebra and&nbsp;
doesn’t really make sense, except in an applied,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:58.610 --> 00:20:04.850
truncated kind of fashion. That’s&nbsp;
the reality of where things are.

00:20:04.850 --> 00:20:11.600
Alright, let’s now turn to this roots of unity&nbsp;
question, which deals with a very simple,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:18.050
seemingly simple, kind of equation—something&nbsp;
like z⁷ = 1. This is a particular example&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:18.050 --> 00:20:24.290
of roots of unity, where the n is 7, so we&nbsp;
end up getting the seventh roots of unity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:24.290 --> 00:20:30.890
supposedly. Almost all modern mathematicians&nbsp;
these days believe that this equation has seven&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:30.890 --> 00:20:37.040
solutions in the complex plane and that they’re&nbsp;
equally spaced around the unit circle—a seventh&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:37.040 --> 00:20:44.540
of a turn between any two of them. The usual&nbsp;
names or symbols for these so-called roots of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:44.540 --> 00:20:49.550
unity are the following: this one, which&nbsp;
is the obvious solution, and then there’s&nbsp;

