00:21:13.430 --> 00:21:20.540
So your typical modern mathematician is absolutely&nbsp;
convinced—no question whatsoever about it—that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:20.540 --> 00:21:24.710
there are exactly seven complex numbers, and here&nbsp;
they are, that are exactly on the unit circle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:24.710 --> 00:21:33.470
equally separated, that are the solutions&nbsp;
to this simple equation, z⁷ = 1. However,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:33.470 --> 00:21:40.940
if you actually try to draw a heptagon, then maybe&nbsp;
some doubt starts to creep into your mind. And if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:40.940 --> 00:21:47.810
you appreciate that the ancients, like the Greeks,&nbsp;
were quite flabbergasted by this problem—how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:47.810 --> 00:21:55.640
do you actually construct a beautiful, regular&nbsp;
heptagon? If you do it by hand like I’ve done,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:55.640 --> 00:22:00.530
you can probably even see just by looking at it&nbsp;
that this is probably not exactly a heptagon.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:00.530 --> 00:22:10.700
It’s actually quite surprisingly hard to draw a&nbsp;
heptagon accurately. In fact, it’s impossible to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:10.700 --> 00:22:18.530
draw it completely accurately, even in principle.&nbsp;
There’s no technology known to mankind that will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:18.530 --> 00:22:28.010
in principle draw a perfect heptagon, a regular&nbsp;
heptagon. This is an interesting thing, okay? And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:28.010 --> 00:22:33.800
we can see this by thinking about how a computer&nbsp;
would draw it. I mean, if you ask your computer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:33.800 --> 00:22:38.330
your computer will draw a very nice-looking&nbsp;
one, but it’s not actually exactly accurate.

00:22:38.330 --> 00:22:45.530
So your computer actually has to calculate where&nbsp;
these points are. It has to convert the sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:45.530 --> 00:22:46.820
symbolic
