00:22:56.345 --> 00:23:04.730
is a kind of short form for cos(2π/7) + i&nbsp;
sin(2π/7). Okay, so we haven’t talked very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:04.730 --> 00:23:09.200
much about these transcendental functions, and&nbsp;
they’re really fraught with difficulties—all of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:15.440
this should actually be in quotes, okay? But just&nbsp;
to give you an overview, the idea is that what you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:15.440 --> 00:23:21.380
have to do in order to find out what this complex&nbsp;
number really is, is you have to evaluate these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:21.380 --> 00:23:32.090
two things. So, cos(2π/7)—well, that’s again&nbsp;
the same kind of difficult story as the tan&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:32.090 --> 00:23:37.700
inverse of 5/12. There’s a certain series, a&nbsp;
certain infinite series, that was well-known,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:37.700 --> 00:23:46.940
goes back a long time, probably even to Hindu&nbsp;
mathematicians, and it’s 1 - 1/2! (2π/7)² + 1/4!&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:47.480 --> 00:23:57.660
(2π/7)⁴ - 1/6! (2π/7)⁶, and so on. So here we&nbsp;
have factorials now, so 4! (for example) means&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:57.660 --> 00:24:06.420
1 * 2 * 3 * 4. So what’s involved here is again&nbsp;
an infinite number of arithmetic operations with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:06.420 --> 00:24:13.260
increasingly more and more complicated things,&nbsp;
and it’s quite clear that you can’t ever really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:13.260 --> 00:24:22.020
do this. In fact, even the definition of this&nbsp;
infinite sum is actually problematic. And then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:22.020 --> 00:24:29.460
there’s a corresponding thing for sin(2π/7) or&nbsp;
a similar kind of series for the imaginary part.

00:24:29.460 --> 00:24:35.010
But our computers don’t fuss around about&nbsp;
this because our computers just truncate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:35.010 --> 00:24:41.520
at some convenient point and spew out some&nbsp;
decimals, which we take. We take the decimals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:41.520 --> 00:24:46.950
that our computer gives, and then we add three&nbsp;
dots, okay? And these three dots represent,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:46.950 --> 00:24:53.340
in our minds, all of that extra infinite amount&nbsp;
of work that we could do, or perhaps should do,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:53.340 --> 00:25:00.630
but we’re not going to do it. And we can&nbsp;
kind of console ourselves that an engineer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:00.630 --> 00:25:05.640
is not concerned about these three dots. So&nbsp;
the engineer comes along and says, “Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:05.640 --> 00:25:11.640
that’s eight decimal places. That’s far more than&nbsp;
I need to be able to put this on the page very,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:11.640 --> 00:25:16.830
very cleanly and clearly. That’s all the&nbsp;
precision I need. I don’t care anything about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:16.830 --> 00:25:27.330
these three dots here.” But the reality is that&nbsp;
an exact understanding of this z is beyond us,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:27.330 --> 00:25:35.430
okay? The point is that we cannot actually get&nbsp;
a hold of this thing. In fact, this thing does&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:35.430 --> 00:25:40.620
not even exist, properly speaking. The right&nbsp;
orientation is that there is no such thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:40.620 --> 00:25:45.240
okay? We’re talking about something&nbsp;
that doesn’t exist as if it did exist.

00:25:45.240 --> 00:25:54.030
And similarly, the fundamental theorem, which&nbsp;
tells us that z⁷ - 1 ought to be the product&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:54.030 --> 00:25:59.130
of all these linear factors corresponding&nbsp;
to all these different seventh roots of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:59.130 --> 00:26:03.310
unity (by the way, which can be expressed&nbsp;
as this is z, and this would be z², z³, z⁴,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:03.310 --> 00:26:10.660
z⁵, z⁶), so there’s a pleasant kind&nbsp;
of algebraic way of writing them down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:10.660 --> 00:26:19.090
like this—this fundamental theorem also doesn’t&nbsp;
really work. So if you plug something like this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:19.090 --> 00:26:24.040
in here and you try to equate the right-hand&nbsp;
side to the left-hand side, you will see that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:24.040 --> 00:26:32.710
it doesn’t work, okay? So it’s a bit of a&nbsp;
dream. It’s an approximation to something,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:32.710 --> 00:26:41.500
okay? But it’s actually algebraically not hanging&nbsp;
together. So, the existence of roots of unity is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:41.500 --> 00:26:45.640
really something that we need to rethink, and&nbsp;
that has a lot of implications for algebra.

00:26:45.640 --> 00:26:51.850
What makes this topic a little bit difficult to&nbsp;
get your head around is that there are, in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:51.850 --> 00:26:58.990
algebraic ways of solving something like z⁷ =&nbsp;
1. It’s not that this equation is beyond us,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:58.990 --> 00:27:06.070
and I’m going to be showing you ways of very&nbsp;
clearly setting up a framework in which we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:06.070 --> 00:27:15.070
seven solutions of that. So there’s a bona fide&nbsp;
algebraic way of dealing with this equation. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:15.070 --> 00:27:20.410
the point is that it’s separate, okay? This&nbsp;
algebraic approach to, say, solving something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:20.410 --> 00:27:28.510
like z⁷ = 1 should be kept separate from the&nbsp;
analytic approach or an analytic approximate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:28.510 --> 00:27:35.230
approach of solving z⁷ = 1 involving seven numbers&nbsp;
on the unit circle, which are equally spaced.

00:27:36.760 --> 00:27:42.790
So, currently, in many algebraic minds—probably&nbsp;
not all, but in many of them—these two things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:42.790 --> 00:27:49.150
are so intimately connected, and they’re just&nbsp;
part of the same story. What I want you to start&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:49.150 --> 00:27:52.540
thinking about is that we have to separate these&nbsp;
things. We’re going to have to push them apart;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:52.540 --> 00:27:59.050
we have to make some space. Over here is&nbsp;
the algebraic approach, purely finite,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:59.050 --> 00:28:06.880
purely algebraic, completely solid.&nbsp;
Over here is the analytic approach,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:06.880 --> 00:28:15.040
where we’re working within the complex numbers,&nbsp;
but almost everything is approximate. We have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:15.040 --> 00:28:20.500
some nice geometry, but the geometry is only&nbsp;
approximate. And these two pictures are really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:20.500 --> 00:28:24.640
different kinds of pictures. There is some&nbsp;
kind of connection between them, and it’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:24.640 --> 00:28:30.160
interesting to explore what the connection&nbsp;
is, but they’re logically separate, okay?

00:28:30.160 --> 00:28:36.370
So, we are going to be trying to turn our&nbsp;
gaze away from this complex number picture&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:36.370 --> 00:28:43.870
that rests on the fundamental theorem of algebra&nbsp;
towards this more algebraic approach to solving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:43.870 --> 00:28:51.490
polynomial equations. In our next video, we&nbsp;
are actually going to start with some abstract&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:51.490 --> 00:28:57.250
algebra. We’re going to look at probably the&nbsp;
simplest kinds of things that we can do, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:57.250 --> 00:29:04.240
are not groups and not fields—they are something&nbsp;
in the direction of linear spaces. So, we’re going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:04.240 --> 00:29:10.030
to concentrate on linear spaces to begin with.&nbsp;
That’s a great starting point for building up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:10.030 --> 00:29:16.120
abstract algebra. I hope you’ll join me for that.&nbsp;
I’m Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

